say this in other talks,

00:14:10.530 --> 00:14:12.190
and I think it's very inspiring.

00:14:12.190 --> 00:14:15.710
"There is no such thing
as gender, race, or class.

00:14:15.710 --> 00:14:17.800
They are cultural inventions.

00:14:17.800 --> 00:14:20.060
We are all linked, not ranked."

00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:22.090
I really thought that was
a beautiful statement.

00:14:22.090 --> 00:14:24.640
Can you tell us what
you meant by that?

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:27.830
GLORIA STEINEM: Yeah,
I've just done an event

00:14:27.830 --> 00:14:31.580
with Ta-Nehisi Coates and
Bryan Stevenson, whose work I

00:14:31.580 --> 00:14:33.800
hope you know, and I hope
you read their books.

00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:39.210
And it was great, because we
were all trying to say this.

00:14:39.210 --> 00:14:42.340
On the one hand,
there is no gender.

00:14:42.340 --> 00:14:43.920
There is no race.

00:14:43.920 --> 00:14:44.960
There is no class.

00:14:44.960 --> 00:14:46.660
There is no caste.

00:14:46.660 --> 00:14:52.730
On the other hand, we as human
beings are very adaptable.

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:54.400
The good news is
that we're adaptable,

00:14:54.400 --> 00:14:56.330
and the bad news is
that we're adaptable.

00:14:56.330 --> 00:15:00.560
We survive, because
we're so adaptable.

00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:03.970
We're born with immature
brains, unlike other animals,

00:15:03.970 --> 00:15:06.850
who can get up and walk
around 20 minutes later.

00:15:06.850 --> 00:15:11.670
So we have a really long
period of dependency.

00:15:11.670 --> 00:15:16.060
So we're deeply adaptable
and influenceable.

00:15:16.060 --> 00:15:23.500
So race, and class, and caste,
and gender are embedded in us.

00:15:23.500 --> 00:15:26.640
But we made them
up as human beings.

00:15:26.640 --> 00:15:28.000
We made them up.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.590
And if you look at
the ancient cultures,

00:15:31.590 --> 00:15:36.220
the original cultures, many
of which are still with us,

00:15:36.220 --> 00:15:39.440
there's not even he and
she in the language.

00:15:39.440 --> 00:15:40.530
There's no gender.

00:15:40.530 --> 00:15:41.590
People are people.

00:15:41.590 --> 00:15:43.800
What a concept.

00:15:43.800 --> 00:15:49.250
There's no word for nature,
because we're part of nature.

00:15:49.250 --> 00:15:54.777
So I think what's great about
Ta-Nehisi's book and Brian's

00:15:54.777 --> 00:15:56.360
book is that they
are saying the same.

00:15:56.360 --> 00:16:02.310
They are trying to make us see
how deep racism is, and sexism

00:16:02.310 --> 00:16:05.390
too, at the same time
that they fully understand

00:16:05.390 --> 00:16:06.790
that it doesn't exist.

00:16:06.790 --> 00:16:09.120
And those, I think,
are the two ideas

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:12.070
we need to go forward with.

00:16:12.070 --> 00:16:14.670
FEMALE SPEAKER: So
as a person of ideas,

00:16:14.670 --> 00:16:18.380
you're someone that really
emphasizes both in your book

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:22.600
but in your life how much
transformative ideas often

00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:24.630
come from unexpected places.

00:16:24.630 --> 00:16:27.740
It's certainly something I
took away in reading the book.

00:16:27.740 --> 00:16:31.020
Of all the people that
you've met, who has really

00:16:31.020 --> 00:16:33.971
had the greatest impact on you?

00:16:33.971 --> 00:16:35.720
GLORIA STEINEM: You
mean I have to choose?

00:16:35.720 --> 00:16:39.610
FEMALE SPEAKER: No, a few.

00:16:39.610 --> 00:16:43.380
GLORIA STEINEM: It's
hard, but I would

00:16:43.380 --> 00:16:46.550
say because I've
been in more touch

00:16:46.550 --> 00:16:49.440
here with people
in Indian Country

00:16:49.440 --> 00:16:55.630
than in other countries, I mean,
it's the original cultures, OK?

00:16:55.630 --> 00:16:58.080
So it's the Khoi and the
San in Africa, which we all

00:16:58.080 --> 00:17:01.700
came from, the Dalits in India.

00:17:01.700 --> 00:17:05.030
But since I live here,
it's Indian Country here.

00:17:09.360 --> 00:17:12.390
I once made a button that said,
the truth will set you free,

00:17:12.390 --> 00:17:13.849
but first it will piss you off.

00:17:17.670 --> 00:17:20.650
Because I was so mad
that nobody ever told me

00:17:20.650 --> 00:17:23.829
what was here before
Columbus showed up,

00:17:23.829 --> 00:17:27.030
that there were pyramids
bigger than the ones in Egypt,

00:17:27.030 --> 00:17:31.900
that there were earthworks, the
biggest system of earthworks

00:17:31.900 --> 00:17:36.910
in the world, that
there were cultures

00:17:36.910 --> 00:17:40.710
with great sophistication
about pharmacology,

00:17:40.710 --> 00:17:46.280
about agriculture, and that
they were what we would call

00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:51.890
egalitarian cultures that
were whose model, at least as

00:17:51.890 --> 00:17:55.590
much as we know, because there
were 500 different ones, whose

00:17:55.590 --> 00:18:00.390
model was the circle,
not a pyramid.

00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:02.940
So people were connected.

00:18:02.940 --> 00:18:06.600
People were linked, not ranked,
and also linked to nature.

00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:14.050
You could do a great
experiment to just

00:18:14.050 --> 00:18:18.430
find out who lived here, and
how did they live right here?

00:18:18.430 --> 00:18:20.910
There's something intimate
about vertical history.

00:18:20.910 --> 00:18:24.090
You can go out and put your
hand on the land and say.

00:18:24.090 --> 00:18:25.890
Who was here and
probably still is here?

00:18:25.890 --> 00:18:29.220
There were more
tribes in California

00:18:29.220 --> 00:18:32.190
than any other part
of the country.

00:18:32.190 --> 00:18:36.580
So on that basis, I would
say that Wilma Mankiller, who

00:18:36.580 --> 00:18:41.630
was the chief of the Cherokee
Nation influenced me the most.

00:18:41.630 --> 00:18:44.420
And she's no longer with
us, but before she died,

00:18:44.420 --> 00:18:46.840
we were trying to
do a book together

00:18:46.840 --> 00:18:49.040
which I'm gonna try to do.

00:18:51.840 --> 00:18:54.440
I mean, I want this
to be practical.

00:18:54.440 --> 00:18:57.340
I don't want it to be
theoretical and out there.

00:18:57.340 --> 00:18:59.040
So I'll give you an example.

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:02.300
We were taking examples
from original cultures

00:19:02.300 --> 00:19:05.640
around the world,
and taking ones

00:19:05.640 --> 00:19:08.810
that we could do to make
a bridge, to keep us

00:19:08.810 --> 00:19:12.470
from thinking, oh that's either
the romantic or terrible past

00:19:12.470 --> 00:19:14.540
or something, but
just practical things.

00:19:14.540 --> 00:19:20.270
For instance, in of the
oldest cultures in Ghana,

00:19:20.270 --> 00:19:24.380
when someone does an
anti-social destructive thing,

00:19:24.380 --> 00:19:27.960
they are indeed
punished with isolation,

00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:31.350
which may be a universal
human punishment, since we're

00:19:31.350 --> 00:19:32.770
communal people.

00:19:32.770 --> 00:19:34.090
We need each other.

00:19:34.090 --> 00:19:35.850
Communal animals.

00:19:35.850 --> 00:19:38.100
Not like our
solitary confinement,

00:19:38.100 --> 00:19:42.960
mind you, just a brief
period of isolation.

00:19:42.960 --> 00:19:47.440
And when that person is
brought back into society,

00:19:47.440 --> 00:19:49.990
there is a long
ritual amount of time

00:19:49.990 --> 00:19:52.020
in which everyone
who knows that person

00:19:52.020 --> 00:19:56.960
tells that person every good
thing he or she ever did.

00:19:56.960 --> 00:19:59.020
We could do that.

00:19:59.020 --> 00:20:01.250
We do the reverse.

00:20:01.250 --> 00:20:02.180
We take votes away.

00:20:02.180 --> 00:20:03.390
We take jobs away.

00:20:03.390 --> 00:20:04.340
We punish forever.

00:20:06.860 --> 00:20:11.300
We've just won a tiny victory
of getting rid of the box

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:14.330
at the beginning
of job applications

00:20:14.330 --> 00:20:17.489
that says whether you've
ever been arrested or not,

00:20:17.489 --> 00:20:19.030
and at least putting
it at the bottom

00:20:19.030 --> 00:20:21.660
after you've seen all
the qualifications.

00:20:21.660 --> 00:20:23.820
So there are a ton
of things like that.

00:20:27.550 --> 00:20:29.730
I mean, I don't know
why we're so-- well,

00:20:29.730 --> 00:20:30.950
history is political.

00:20:30.950 --> 00:20:32.130
We should remember that.

00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:34.150
There are two things--
history and the past,

00:20:34.150 --> 00:20:36.709
and they're not the same.

00:20:36.709 --> 00:20:38.000
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's so true.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.840
We had the opportunity to
be deeply inspired by Bryan

00:20:40.840 --> 00:20:43.360
Stevenson recently.

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:45.190
He was at Google Zeitgeist.

00:20:45.190 --> 00:20:47.040
So for anyone one
here at Google,

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:49.630
you can go on to watch
the videos from Zeitgeist,

00:20:49.630 --> 00:20:53.120
one of the most compelling talks
I've ever heard in my life.

00:20:53.120 --> 00:20:55.770
And I think genuinely
many people talk about him

00:20:55.770 --> 00:20:59.440
as the next Martin Luther King,
really pushing the thinking

00:20:59.440 --> 00:21:01.810
on that concept of
what we're doing

00:21:01.810 --> 00:21:05.370
as a society and our
collective responsibility.

00:21:05.370 --> 00:21:09.480
As I think about so
many of the passages

00:21:09.480 --> 00:21:12.610
in this book, another one
I wanted to highlight,

00:21:12.610 --> 00:21:14.855
because I think it's
so relevant to us

00:21:14.855 --> 00:21:18.510
at Google and as a leader,
you wrote in the book,

00:21:18.510 --> 00:21:21.200
"one of the simplest
paths to deep change

00:21:21.200 --> 00:21:26.360
is for the more powerful to
listen as much as they speak."

00:21:26.360 --> 00:21:29.140
And that really made
me think about so many

00:21:29.140 --> 00:21:31.210
of the conversations
that we've had.

00:21:31.210 --> 00:21:33.340
And I think that inspiration
I always find from you

00:21:33.340 --> 00:21:36.290
is that connection
to something deeper,

00:21:36.290 --> 00:21:41.181
to that historical context,
to all that framework.

00:21:41.181 --> 00:21:43.805
How did you learn to become such
a good listener and connector?

00:21:46.850 --> 00:21:49.800
GLORIA STEINEM: I think
we choose our professions

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:54.060
a little bit on our
persona, what we want to do.

00:21:54.060 --> 00:21:59.330
So I have wanted to be two
things in my life, a dancer,

00:21:59.330 --> 00:22:01.520
because I had the
completely bonkers idea that

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:03.180
was gonna get me out of Toledo.

00:22:03.180 --> 00:22:06.580
I was gonna dance my
way out of Toledo.

00:22:06.580 --> 00:22:09.680
Because I think show
business is to girls

00:22:09.680 --> 00:22:11.020
what sports is to boys.

00:22:11.020 --> 00:22:13.490
It's the only way, or at
least in poor neighborhoods,

00:22:13.490 --> 00:22:15.040
it's the only place you
see somebody who looks

00:22:15.040 --> 00:22:16.210
like you who's getting out.

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:22.040
A dancer and a writer,
and as a speech teacher

00:22:22.040 --> 00:22:24.010
said to me, no wonder
you're in such trouble

00:22:24.010 --> 00:22:26.640
speaking-- because
I was terrified.

00:22:26.640 --> 00:22:30.460
Those are the two professions
in which you don't have to talk.

00:22:34.230 --> 00:22:42.400
So I once wrote a long essay
about the politics of talking.

00:22:42.400 --> 00:22:45.934
Because I also believed that
women talk more than men do.

00:22:45.934 --> 00:22:47.850
I thought it's probably
one of the few ways we

00:22:47.850 --> 00:22:49.480
can show our power.

00:22:49.480 --> 00:22:51.640
But the studies are
the reverse, actually.

00:22:51.640 --> 00:22:55.140
In general, men talk more than
women do, even about subjects

00:22:55.140 --> 00:22:56.080
of female expertise.

00:22:58.600 --> 00:23:03.870
And what happens is that
women introduce topics

00:23:03.870 --> 00:23:09.220
until one captures the attention
of the men in the group,

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:10.840
and continue with it.

00:23:10.840 --> 00:23:14.170
Whereas men-- I'm
sorry to generalize,

00:23:14.170 --> 00:23:17.320
because I'm sure that it's not
true of the men in this room,

00:23:17.320 --> 00:23:21.770
but in a kind of
sociological way--

00:23:21.770 --> 00:23:25.410
whereas men feel completely
comfortable sitting

00:23:25.410 --> 00:23:29.040
there talking about their work
while women are listening.

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:30.630
And women don't do that.

00:23:30.630 --> 00:23:32.030
If the men are
not participating,

00:23:32.030 --> 00:23:35.690
they get anxious and start
to introduce other subjects.

00:23:35.690 --> 00:23:39.310
So just the politics of
talking interested me.

00:23:39.310 --> 00:23:46.110
And I realized from living
in India-- it's a long story,

00:23:46.110 --> 00:23:51.260
but anyway, if you want
people to listen to you,

00:23:51.260 --> 00:23:53.330
you have to listen to them.

00:23:53.330 --> 00:23:57.990
And if you have
not been powerful,

00:23:57.990 --> 00:24:01.440
you have to speak as much
as you listen if you're not

00:24:01.440 --> 00:24:05.330
the powerful one in this group.

00:24:05.330 --> 00:24:07.970
And sometimes,
that's as difficult.

00:24:07.970 --> 00:24:11.360
Because those of us
who may have been

00:24:11.360 --> 00:24:14.370
in a position of lesser power
have protected ourselves

00:24:14.370 --> 00:24:16.210
by not talking.

00:24:16.210 --> 00:24:22.260
I mean, I felt like an open
mouthed bird in flight, just

00:24:22.260 --> 00:24:25.420
the first time when
I began to talk.

00:24:25.420 --> 00:24:27.360
I felt so vulnerable.

00:24:27.360 --> 00:24:30.360
But if you balance
talking and listening,

00:24:30.360 --> 00:24:32.985
it's a very organic
step to equality.

00:24:34.934 --> 00:24:36.850
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's
actually very profound,

00:24:36.850 --> 00:24:39.500
an organic step to equality,
talking and listening.

00:24:39.500 --> 00:24:41.890
I think that's one thing I
could definitely take out

00:24:41.890 --> 00:24:45.450
of this room to really commit,
because I do think that's

00:24:45.450 --> 00:24:47.550
one of the biggest
challenges as a leader is

00:24:47.550 --> 00:24:50.260
to ensure that you're
listening as much as talking.

00:24:50.260 --> 00:24:52.760
As you talked about people that
influenced you, in the book,

00:24:52.760 --> 00:24:55.290
you talked a lot
about your father

00:24:55.290 --> 00:24:57.840
and what a profound
impact he had on you.

00:24:57.840 --> 00:25:00.110
And it also sounds like a
complicated relationship,

00:25:00.110 --> 00:25:03.730
because it was harder
for you to attend school

00:25:03.730 --> 00:25:05.070
through the age of 11.

00:25:05.070 --> 00:25:10.490
How did that experience in the
world shape you as a person?

00:25:10.490 --> 00:25:12.490
GLORIA STEINEM:
Well, at the time,

00:25:12.490 --> 00:25:17.120
my father was kind of a
gypsy, I should explain.

00:25:17.120 --> 00:25:18.050
We lived in Michigan.

00:25:18.050 --> 00:25:19.300
He had a little summer resort.

00:25:19.300 --> 00:25:20.900
He hated the cold
weather, so as soon

00:25:20.900 --> 00:25:23.540
as it got cold at
Halloween, I left school,

00:25:23.540 --> 00:25:27.200
and we all got in the house
trailer and schlepped, buying

00:25:27.200 --> 00:25:30.280
and selling antiques, to
Florida or California.

00:25:33.134 --> 00:25:34.300
So I wasn't going to school.

00:25:34.300 --> 00:25:36.716
And of course I wanted to go
to school like the other kids

00:25:36.716 --> 00:25:39.220
I saw in movies.

00:25:39.220 --> 00:25:42.260
But in retrospect, I realized
that it was probably not bad,

00:25:42.260 --> 00:25:46.402
because I missed a
lot of brainwashing.

00:25:46.402 --> 00:25:48.235
I didn't read all those
Dick and Jane books.

00:25:52.130 --> 00:25:53.160
I paid a penalty.

00:25:53.160 --> 00:25:56.050
I still can't add, subtract,
and my geography is nowhere,

00:25:56.050 --> 00:26:00.220
but my vocabulary is
off the-- because I

00:26:00.220 --> 00:26:01.840
was reading all the time.

00:26:01.840 --> 00:26:03.530
But still, I think
it was important

00:26:03.530 --> 00:26:05.610
that I missed that
kind of brainwashing.

00:26:05.610 --> 00:26:10.250
And also, I have to say
that it was important

00:26:10.250 --> 00:26:14.520
that my father treated me
like a buddy, a friend.

00:26:14.520 --> 00:26:18.110
His favorite story about me
was that when I was, like,

00:26:18.110 --> 00:26:20.870
five or something, we went
to a little country store,

00:26:20.870 --> 00:26:22.880
and I asked him for a nickel.

00:26:22.880 --> 00:26:24.380
And he said what for?

00:26:24.380 --> 00:26:26.810
And according to him, I
said you can give it to me

00:26:26.810 --> 00:26:29.240
or not give it to me, but
you can't ask what it's for.

00:26:32.340 --> 00:26:33.970
And to me, this
story is about him,

00:26:33.970 --> 00:26:35.427
because he said that's right.

00:26:35.427 --> 00:26:36.510
And he gave me the nickel.

00:26:38.410 --> 00:26:40.410
FEMALE SPEAKER: I thought
that was pretty great.

00:26:40.410 --> 00:26:43.570
A good negotiator,
even early on.

00:26:43.570 --> 00:26:46.780
So given it's election season,
I can avoid this topic,

00:26:46.780 --> 00:26:49.350
because you've been such a
passionate supporter of women

00:26:49.350 --> 00:26:51.170
getting into public office.

00:26:51.170 --> 00:26:54.850
You're a vocal Hillary
Clinton supporter.

00:26:54.850 --> 00:26:56.350
Are things different
for Hillary now

00:26:56.350 --> 00:27:00.020
than they were
the last election?

00:27:00.020 --> 00:27:04.566
GLORIA STEINEM: My sense is
that they are, but we'll see.

00:27:04.566 --> 00:27:06.840
If you'll remember
the last time,

00:27:06.840 --> 00:27:10.210
I mean, first of all,
it was not so urgent,

00:27:10.210 --> 00:27:12.530
because you had to
be on LSD to see

00:27:12.530 --> 00:27:17.080
the difference between
Hillary and Obama on issues.

00:27:17.080 --> 00:27:19.260
The whole first year
people, would say

00:27:19.260 --> 00:27:21.111
are you supporting
Hillary Clinton or Obama,

00:27:21.111 --> 00:27:21.985
and I would say, yes.

00:27:25.310 --> 00:27:28.180
But she had so much more
experience with the ultra right

00:27:28.180 --> 00:27:32.410
wing, which is so crucial.

00:27:32.410 --> 00:27:35.820
And I think that the lack
of that experience for Obama

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:37.380
made it harder for
him in Washington

00:27:37.380 --> 00:27:40.250
in the first couple of years,
because being a good person,

00:27:40.250 --> 00:27:45.550
he thought he could reach out
and somehow this would work.

00:27:45.550 --> 00:27:48.215
And he didn't quite realize that
if the right wing had cancer,

00:27:48.215 --> 00:27:50.090
and he had the cure,
they wouldn't accept it.

00:27:56.470 --> 00:27:58.950
But then, even though
I supported her

00:27:58.950 --> 00:28:02.680
based on her experience, I
didn't think that she could

00:28:02.680 --> 00:28:09.090
win, because I thought that
too few people had seen women

00:28:09.090 --> 00:28:12.660
in public authority,
and almost all of us

00:28:12.660 --> 00:28:17.840
have seen female authority
in childhood, which I think

00:28:17.840 --> 00:28:21.500
is why some of the big,
serious television guys

00:28:21.500 --> 00:28:24.930
behaved so badly,
and said things like,

00:28:24.930 --> 00:28:28.200
she reminds me of my first
wife outside alimony court,

00:28:28.200 --> 00:28:31.020
and I cross my legs
whenever I see Hilary.

